d the insurance piece each plays\n\nWith US **unemployment rising to 4.4%** after nonfarm payrolls decreased by 701k in March, we lean on our GIR Guide to estimate real-time GDP trending (*see US Daily\u00a0attachment*) \u2026 we still see weak demand and high unemployment as a reliable recipe for lower inflation\n\nAs unemployment rises, we see the relationship as being roughly 1:1\u2026 **1pp increase in unemployment, 1pp decrease in GDP**\u2026 Reducing GDP activity by 13% in April (*see US Economics Analyst\u00a0attachment*)\n\nMarket Direction\n\nWe have likely seen the highs of vol and implied vol\u2026 Markets won\u2019t be surprised by defaults or layoffs.. Systematic selling is done, but the retail market remains the wild card\u2026 Likely to see a **positive correlation between a rise in jobless claims/unemployment with U.S. equity outflows** from retail community as people have to dip into 401k\u2019s, brokerage accounts to pay credit cards, auto loans, mortgages, etc\u2026\n\nFrom our Securities Division Index desk\u2026 Trading in S&P futures has been range bound (2300-2800)\u2026 market\u2019s **expectation for the U.S. economy is to open back up in mid-late May**.. opening any later would likely send the markets lower\n\nCharts and Tables\n\nA handy chart from Ben Snider in GIR\u2026 Macro variables and their effect on S&P earnings\n\nhttps://preview.redd.it/j1pkov5vq7r41.png?width=574&format=png&auto=webp&s=bf1e420b091468c3dcd0f439b48e01d9eadcd4d7\n\n&#x200B;\n\nWe talk about how fast things happened and the chart below helps put this time period in perspective\n\nhttps://preview.redd.it/zn2ei1jvq7r41.png?width=632&format=png&auto=webp&s=6833d67c448957744dbff5eb0ec8bb4def3d3d2a\n\n&#x200B;\n\nBuybacks have acted as a support level for equity markets since the GFC\u2026 Of the top 25 S&P re-purchasers in 2019, 6 have announced suspensions so far..\n\nhttps://preview.redd.it/ozibnmxvq7r41.png?width=852&format=png&auto=webp&s=8e61a55fb39ca7fe3497f138fdf